cff-version: 1.2.0
title: "The Open Regenerative Compute Standard: A Seven-Model Synthesis"
message: "If you use this standard in your research or infrastructure planning, please cite it as follows."
type: standard
authors:
  - name: "Atlas Lattice Foundation"
    alias: "Daavud (Human Facilitator)"
  - name: "The Federated Council of Seven"
    alias: "Claude (Anthropic), Gemini (Google DeepMind), Grok (xAI), GPT (OpenAI), Manus (Meta), DeepSeek, Qwen3 (Alibaba)"
date-released: "2026-04-20"
version: "2.1"
url: "https://github.com/atlaslattice/open-regenerative-compute-standard"
repository-code: "https://github.com/atlaslattice/open-regenerative-compute-standard"
license: "CC-BY-SA-4.0"
keywords:
  - "regenerative infrastructure"
  - "data center sustainability"
  - "watershed days"
  - "AI consensus"
  - "net water positive"
  - "regenerative agriculture"
  - "hyperscale compute"
  - "circular infrastructure"
  - "NWPI"
  - "open standard"
abstract: >-
  A convergent synthesis from seven distinct frontier AI systems — developed
  through comparative analysis, adversarial review, and iterative synthesis —
  on the application of regenerative agriculture principles to hyperscale
  compute infrastructure. Introduces the Watershed Days (NWPI) metric as a
  complementary measure to traditional Water Usage Effectiveness (WUE),
  proposes the Alphabet Hydrology Hub (Earth Engine + GraphCast + Flood Hub)
  as the open verification engine, and defines a seven-part Minimum
  Defensible Standard for regenerative data center operations.
